Solution 9.13. Let $\mathbf{x}^{\mu} = \mathbf{x}^{\mu}(\lambda, \mathfrak{n})$ be a family of geodesics with affine parameter $\lambda$ . The parameter $\mathfrak{n}$ labels the individual geodesics. The tangent to the geodesics is $\mathfrak{u}^a \equiv \partial \mathbf{x}^a / \partial \lambda$ and the differential vector which connects points of equal affine parameter on adjacent curves is$$\mathbf {n}^{\alpha} = \partial \mathbf {x}^{\alpha} / \partial \mathbf {n}.$$The solution to this problem is most transparent in abstract notation:Write$$\mathbf {u} = \partial / \partial \lambda , \quad \mathbf {n} = \partial / \partial \mathbf {n}.$$Note that $[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{n}] = 0$ since the partial derivatives commute. (The vanishing of this commutator in fact is the definition of $\mathbf{n}$ as the connecting vector, according to Problem 8.14.) Now use the Riemann operator (see Problem 9.12):$$\mathbf {R} (\mathbf {u}, \mathbf {n}) \mathbf {u} \equiv 
abla_{\mathbf {u}} 
abla_{\mathbf {n}} \mathbf {u} - 
abla_{\mathbf {n}} 
abla_{\mathbf {u}} \mathbf {u} - 
abla_{[ \mathbf {u}, \mathbf {n} ]} \mathbf {u} = 
abla_{\mathbf {u}} 
abla_{\mathbf {n}} \mathbf {u} = 
abla_{\mathbf {u}} 
abla_{\mathbf {u}} \mathbf {n} ,$$where the last equality follows from the vanishing of $[\mathbf{u},\mathbf{n}]$ . In components our result, according to Problem 9.12(b), reads$$ rac {\mathrm {D}^{2} \mathbf {\hat {n}}^{\alpha}}{\mathrm {d} \lambda^{2}} = (
